## Customers, pricing, and revenue

### Customer segments

The platform has three primary customer groups.

**Facilitators** need visibility, repeat attendance, easier communication of norms and logistics, and a way to benefit from community overlap without running separate stacks across messaging apps, spreadsheets, and event platforms. They are usually price-sensitive and often operate on inconsistent monthly income. They will pay when the product clearly reduces admin and increases repeat attendance. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn36search0Ņłéturn35view0Ņłéturn30search5Ņłü

**Community stewards** need a home for community identity, event continuity, newcomer orientation, and shared responsibility across hosts and venues. Their willingness to pay is higher than that of solo facilitators if the platform truly becomes the sceneŌĆÖs public-facing layer. This segment cares less about individual ticket margins and more about coherence, stewardship, and continuity. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn14search15Ņłéturn32view1Ņłéturn15search4Ņłü

**Participants** want discovery, orientation, and repeat participation. They are unlikely to be an attractive direct-pay segment in the MVP. The best strategy is to keep the participant experience free, friction-light, and trust-building. Premium consumer monetization, if ever introduced, should come later and only if it clearly helps orientation rather than adding status pressure. This matches the dominant market norm across consumer discovery tools. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn15search3Ņłéturn34search6Ņłéturn8search7Ņłéturn7search4Ņłü

